  "prompt": "What are some functions of human cell membranes?",
  "response": "Here are several key functions of human cell membranes:\n\n1. Selective Permeability\n- Controls what enters and exits the cell\n- Allows certain molecules to pass through while blocking others\n- Maintains cellular homeostasis\n\n2. Cell Protection\n- Acts as a protective barrier\n- Separates internal cellular components from external environment\n- Prevents unwanted substances from entering the cell\n\n3. Cell Communication\n- Contains receptor proteins for signal transduction\n- Enables interactions with other cells and external molecules\n- Facilitates communication between cells\n\n4. Cellular Transport\n- Facilitates passive and active transport of molecules\n- Includes mechanisms like diffusion, osmosis, and active transport\n- Moves nutrients, ions, and waste products across the membrane\n\n5. Cellular Recognition\n- Contains glycoproteins and markers that identify cell type\n- Allows immune system to distinguish between self and non-self cells\n- Enables cell-to-cell interactions\n\n6. Enzymatic Activity\n- Contains embedded enzymes that facilitate various biochemical reactions\n- Supports metabolic processes\n\n7. Cell Signaling\n- Hosts receptors for hormones and neurotransmitters\n- Enables cellular response to external stimuli\n\nThese functions are critical for maintaining cellular health and overall physiological processes.",
